{# Conceptual Model benefits #}

<div class="container px-4 py-5">
  <h2 class="pb-2 border-bottom">Complete Data Warehouse Automation based on a Conceptual Model</h2>

  <p class="lead">
      Other Data Warehouse Automation approaches require extensive Data Vault know-how and expensive expertise. 
      The hoped-for increase in efficiency is often not achieved.
      Data Warehouse Automation, on the other hand, becomes very efficient when Data Vault modelling is fully automated and is no longer required.
  </p>

  <h3 class="fw-bold fs-4">Highest level of automation</h3>

  <div class="row row-cols-1 row-cols-sm-2 row-cols-md-3 row-cols-lg-3 g-4 py-3">
    <div class="col d-flex align-items-start">
      <svg class="text-body-secondary flex-shrink-0 me-3" width="2em" height="2em"><use xlink:href="#1-circle"></use></svg>
      <div>
        <h3 class="fw-bold mb-0 fs-5 text-body-emphasis">Automated data modelling</h3>
        <p>
          If the Data Warehouse is automated based on the Conceptual Model, the physical AND logical data modelling for Data Vault can be derived completely. 
          Data Vault expertise is no longer required.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="col d-flex align-items-start">
      <svg class="text-body-secondary flex-shrink-0 me-3" width="2em" height="2em"><use xlink:href="#1-circle"></use></svg>
      <div>
        <h3 class="fw-bold mb-0 fs-5 text-body-emphasis">Fully automated Data Vault</h3>
        <p>
          Yotilla's conceptual model not only contains an mapping of the business objects to the sources, but also the necessary business logic, which is why Yotilla fully automates both the Raw Vault and the Business Vault.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="col d-flex align-items-start">
      <svg class="text-body-secondary flex-shrink-0 me-3" width="2em" height="2em"><use xlink:href="#1-circle"></use></svg>
      <div>
        <h3 class="fw-bold mb-0 fs-5 text-body-emphasis">Automated ETL processes</h3>
        <p>
          As all dependencies are known in Yotilla's Conceptual Model, it is sufficient to start the ETL process for the respective source when new data is delivered. 
            All further process steps are automatically generated, orchestrated and executed by Yotilla.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3 class="fw-bold fs-4">Simple data integration</h3>
    
  <div class="row row-cols-1 row-cols-sm-2 row-cols-md-3 row-cols-lg-3 g-4 py-3">  
    <div class="col d-flex align-items-start">
      <svg class="text-body-secondary flex-shrink-0 me-3" width="2em" height="2em"><use xlink:href="#1-circle"></use></svg>
      <div>
        <h3 class="fw-bold mb-0 fs-4 text-body-emphasis">Consolidated attributes from multiple sources</h3>
        <p>
          Business objects and attributes are mapped to data sources in the Conceptual Model. 
          Attributes whose data originates from multiple sources are automatically identified and consolidated.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="col d-flex align-items-start">
      <svg class="text-body-secondary flex-shrink-0 me-3" width="2em" height="2em"><use xlink:href="#1-circle"></use></svg>
      <div>
        <h3 class="fw-bold mb-0 fs-4 text-body-emphasis">Early transformations</h3>
        <p>
          Source-specific transformations homogenise attributes that originate from multiple sources, e.g. if data types or formats differ. The specified transformations are applied automatically and integrate the data.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="col d-flex align-items-start">
      <svg class="text-body-secondary flex-shrink-0 me-3" width="2em" height="2em"><use xlink:href="#1-circle"></use></svg>
      <div>
        <h3 class="fw-bold mb-0 fs-4 text-body-emphasis">Separating multiple business objects within a source</h3>
        <p>
          A source can contain data from several business objects. Based on the relationships between the business objects in the conceptual model, these can be automatically stored separately and integrated into the data warehouse.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3 class="fw-bold fs-4">Business logic</h3>

  <div class="row row-cols-1 row-cols-sm-2 row-cols-md-3 row-cols-lg-3 g-4 py-3">
    <div class="col d-flex align-items-start">
      <svg class="text-body-secondary flex-shrink-0 me-3" width="2em" height="2em"><use xlink:href="#1-circle"></use></svg>
      <div>
        <h3 class="fw-bold mb-0 fs-4 text-body-emphasis">Customised business logic as part of the Conceptual Model</h3>
        <p>
          The required business objects and attributes can be specified in the Conceptual Model for customised business logic.
          This enables Yotilla to provide the required data within a view that can be accessed to define the customised busines logic with SQL and without data vault expertise.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="col d-flex align-items-start">
      <svg class="text-body-secondary flex-shrink-0 me-3" width="2em" height="2em"><use xlink:href="#1-circle"></use></svg>
      <div>
        <h3 class="fw-bold mb-0 fs-4 text-body-emphasis">Business logic as formula</h3>
        <p>
          Simple business logic can also be specified as a scalar formula that uses business objects and attributes directly. 
          As the relationships of the business objects are known in the Conceptual Model, the implementation of the formula can be fully automated.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="col d-flex align-items-start">
      <svg class="text-body-secondary flex-shrink-0 me-3" width="2em" height="2em"><use xlink:href="#1-circle"></use></svg>
      <div>
        <h3 class="fw-bold mb-0 fs-4 text-body-emphasis">Automated Data Marts</h3>
        <p>
          In the Conceptual Model, define which attributes are to be provided as a dimension or as a fact in the data mart of the data warehouse.
          As all dependencies of the generated Data Vault model are known, the Data Marts are also generated automatically.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

</div>


